name: 1,2-dimethyloxyethane
source: Aldrich Chemical Company; Aldrich Catalog-Handbook of Fine Chemicals; Milwaukee; WI; 1984.
Reason:
The compound 1,2-dimethyloxyethane consists of an ethane backbone with two methoxy groups (-OCH3). To estimate its melting point, we consider the following: 
- The basic unit, ethane, has a melting point of approximately -172°C. 
- Each methoxy group (+OCH3) will introduce additional polarity to the molecule due to the presence of the oxygen atom. Polarity tends to increase the melting point because the molecules can form dipole-dipole interactions, which are stronger than the dispersion forces present in nonpolar molecules like ethane. This might increase the melting point by about +20°C for each methoxy group. 
- However, the added flexibility of the molecule due to the ether linkages (-O-) can reduce the melting point as it lowers the crystal packing efficiency. This might decrease the melting point by about -10°C for each methoxy group linkage. 
Combining these effects, the net increase in the melting point per methoxy group can be estimated to be around +10°C.
- Since there are two methoxy groups in 1,2-dimethyloxyethane, the total effect would be approximately +20°C.
